    <title>Combined summary - Managing block size the same way we do difficulty (aka Block75)</title>
    <updated>2023-06-11T20:55:13.584550+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2016-December/013346.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The discussion surrounding Bitcoin's block size has raised several concerns and considerations about how to manage it. One proposal, Block75, suggests adjusting the maximum block size every two weeks using a system similar to how difficulty is calculated. The target capacity over 2016 blocks would be 75%. However, critics argue that there should be a maximum block size as a consensus rule and that the proposed method can also be gamed by filling the network with transactions.The conversation also touches on the mining aspect of Bitcoin's security model and the potential for a 51% attack. Pieter Wuille argues that optimizing for minimal orphan rate may result in a single entity providing all double spend protection, which goes against the central principle of Bitcoin security. Daniele Pinna questions whether an unrecognizable 51% attack is possible, where the remaining 49% are dragged in against their will.One sender of an email argues that there will always be transactions available to mine due to the unbounded demand for blockspace even as fees approach zero. They also suggest that not sending a transaction would not make blocks smaller since other transactions would still be available. The receiver of the email suggests that miners would try to maximize transaction fees by maxing out the blocks they mine, but points out potential issues with the proposed increase in block size.The sender clarifies that Block75 is not exponential scaling and realistically, the max block size will grow and shrink at a much slower pace, especially with SegWit. Overall, the discussion highlights various concerns and considerations surrounding proposals for managing Bitcoin's block size. Critics argue that there should be a maximum block size as a consensus rule, while others suggest adjusting the maximum block size every two weeks using a system similar to how difficulty is calculated.While the Block75 proposal offers a predictable and effective way to manage Bitcoin's maximum block size, some members of the community argue that this proposal effectively makes the blocksize limit completely uncapped and does not differentiate between genuine transactions and low-value spam attacks. Moreover, the proposed doubling of block size every year proposal may cause major problems as miners may max out the blocks they mine to get more transaction fees. Ultimately, there needs to be a consensus rule for the maximum block size, but the Block75 system provides an automated and scalable solution that can potentially prevent wild swings in block size or transaction fees.Bitcoin's fundamental design allows it to scale by using off-chain solutions, but the need for on-chain scaling may still arise regardless of which off-chain solution gains popularity. The Block75 system cannot be gamed by miners due to the lack of financial incentives, and even attempting to do so would cost more in transaction fees than they could make up. However, it is possible for a miner to create thousands of transactions paying to themselves and hold them instead of broadcasting them to the network, which would allow them to collect the fees included in the blocks they mine.The conversation also discusses the different types of strategies observed in empirical game theory on the network, including altruistic, honest, semi-honest, rational, and dishonest players. There are other proposals, such as Bitcoin Unlimited's EB/AD scheme and BIP100, which recognize miner implementation of the max blocksize but have different approaches to defining the timing of max blocksize increases.</summary>
